<h4 id="prpress">PR/Press</h4>

<p><strong>Scope</strong> Can drive visitors but NOT a business-creating source of traffic.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>About 3 months into launching HowAboutWe we had a full-page front-page print article in the New York Times Sunday Styles section. It was literally the best non-TV press we could have gotten. It drove more traffic than we‚Äôd ever had by about 10x. It was an awesome achievement at that stage. Four years later, while an article like that would have been great, it would have driven a nearly indiscernible increase in traffic. It would be a cool, small, irrelevant bump. For early stage startups we were probably in the top 2 percentile for press converge. And this was key for branding and so on. But it was categorically NOT a business-creating source of traffic. This is very hard to understand for new entrepreneurs. They imbue press ‚Äî like most things ‚Äî with a magical aura of inexplicable growth creating powers.  - <a href="https://andrewchen.co/iacs-howaboutwe-co-founder-how-to-avoid-delusional-thinking-in-start-up-growth-strategy-guest-post/">Aaron Schildkrout, founder of How About We</a></p>
</blockquote>

<p>How? You probably need someone like Trello‚Äôs <a href="https://mixergy.com/free-first-sections-pr-on-a-budget-course/">Stella Farman</a></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Well, congratulations on it. I can‚Äôt end this without saying thank you to Stella for introducing us. Stella Garber is amazing.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>Michael</em>: I had my eye on her for a long time. I had worked with her or I had seen her and talked to her and seen what she had done at a previous company. I knew when I started Trello I had to get her.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>Andrew</em>: For PR, you mean, you saw what she did there?</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>Michael</em>: Yeah. I remember poking at that over the years. There was never like a right position for her. But when it came up‚Ä¶ she had a startup at the time that she was working on. So, it took a little bit of convincing. But I‚Äôm really excited to be working with her.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>Andrew</em>: I‚Äôve always been amazed by the way she promotes the companies she works with. It‚Äôs a human touch that also understands my position. I wanted to have you on, but how do I have you on? How do I tell her I‚Äôm not sure what to do with this? Well, she totally understood and she said, ‚ÄúLook, here‚Äôs the angle that we could take and here‚Äôs some research that will help make this into a great interview,‚Äù which I now have on my screen here.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>For anyone who hasn‚Äôt seen her, her name used to be before she got married Stella Fayman. She did one of the first Mixergy courses where she taught how she gets publicity for the companies she works with. You‚Äôve got to go and watch it. She‚Äôs fantastic. If you ever get to go see her at a conference, go see her.</p>
</blockquote>

<p><strong>Playbook</strong></p>

<p><strong>Use Mechanical Turk + Google News API to hack your own PR</strong></p>

<p>The brilliant people at <a href="http://customerdevlabs.com/">Customer Development Labs</a> have created a press hack where you can easily get the e-mails of all the journalists who are most likely to cover your startup. See complete guide <a href="http://customerdevlabs.com/2013/09/24/google-news-api-mturk-press/">here</a>.</p>

<ol>
  <li>Go to http://press.customerdevlabs.com/</li>
  <li>Search a term that‚Äôs related to your startup category (e.g. SaaS, social media, hologram, kickstarter etc) and download the CSV.</li>
  <li>Upload the CSV to Mechanical Turk.</li>
  <li>Give instructions to your workers on how to <a href="https://www.distilled.net/blog/miscellaneous/find-almost-anybodys-email-address/">find anybody‚Äôs e-mail address</a>.</li>
  <li>Build a press kit. Download <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/mk520mxe2wh8pqo/Press%20Kit%20Sample.zip?dl=0">my example here</a>.</li>
  <li>E-mail the reporters individually and pitch your startup. <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1MEIzcW5Kzp2VGhpnwakKbgdZMKgNAiAuZjbMGLa-odo/edit?usp=sharing">See sample pitch e-mails here</a></li>
</ol>

<p><a href="http://www.producthunt.com/@casinellig/collections/pr-hacks">Other PR hacks curated by Giovanni</a></p>

<p><strong>Turn every conversation with the media into a conversation about the vision</strong></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>‚ÄúWhat makes a company like Uber get covered is not the fact that it‚Äôs a taxi service; it‚Äôs the story that Uber is completely changing the transportation industry. If companies like Uber only talked about what they did now, they‚Äôd be boring and they‚Äôd only get a fraction of the media coverage.‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>When you‚Äôre a startup just getting traction, you can‚Äôt offer the salary and benefits that a world-class employee would normally get at a large company. You haven‚Äôt accomplished a lot that you can talk to the media about. So, what you‚Äôre always selling is the sizzle; not the steak. The sizzle is your vision!‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Quarterly Vision Document Emails: Herold advises his clients to send out the vivid vision quarterly to their customers, ‚Äú90% clients may not care, but even if just a few do, you‚Äôll be able to take your relationship to a whole new level.‚Äù</p>

<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KlekeNwOGHw">YC: How to think about PR?</a></p>

