<h4 id="online-content">Online Content</h4>

<p><strong>Scope: it does not provide a business-supporting customer acquisition channel unless content is your product, but OKCupid did it. wonderful for branding. And if you have a product with high lifetime values, it can easily pay for itself.</strong></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>HowAboutWe has a highly successful blog strategy rooted in <a href="http://thedatereport.com/">thedatereport.com</a> and <a href="http://nerve.com/">nerve.com</a>. But as a pure traffic-driver into our dating product, it was never, well, magical. Let‚Äôs say (none of these are real numbers) 100,000 people visited our articles each day. The conversion to the dating site is basically a glorified advertising system ‚Äî so let‚Äôs say 1% of visitors click-thru. That‚Äôs 1,000 visitors. If we get a 20% conversion rates off those visitors, that‚Äôs 200 sign ups. If we have a 10% conversion to paid, that‚Äôs 20 paid users per day. Let‚Äôs say paid users are worth $100 to us. That‚Äôs ~$2,000 per day. That‚Äôs a bit over half a million bucks per year. Not bad; but it‚Äôs not a significant business. Content is cool, but not magic.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>[Founder] credits content marketing in the form of blogging with OKCupid‚Äôs big success. As well as allowing Google to scrape content from the site for SEO, while competing sites hid everything behind a membership or paywall.</p>
</blockquote>

